    "@id": canonical,
  },
  isPartOf: {
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "@id": `${SITE.url.replace(/\/$/, "")}/bs-en-1176/`,
  },
};

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What is the difference between BS EN 1176 and BS EN 1177?",
    a: "BS EN 1176 covers play equipment itself — design, manufacture, installation, inspection and maintenance. BS EN 1177 is the companion standard covering impact-attenuating surfacing beneath that equipment. BS EN 1176 specifies when surfacing is required (fall height above 600 mm) and to what fall height it must perform; BS EN 1177 specifies the test methodology surfacing must pass to demonstrate that performance. The two standards are designed to be used together.",
  },
  {
    q: "Is wetpour safer than bark?",
    a: "Neither material is inherently safer than the other — both can be rated for use at a given critical fall height if installed to the correct specification. What differs is the nature of their performance and the failure modes. Wetpour maintains its performance consistently unless damaged, but degrades visibly over years and can fail locally without obvious warning. Loose-fill bark performs well when at depth but loses performance rapidly if it migrates, compacts or becomes contaminated. The right choice depends on site conditions, maintenance budget, and accessibility requirements — not on one material being safer than the other in principle.",
  },
  {
    q: "How often must playground surfacing be tested?",
    a: "BS EN 1177 does not mandate a specific retest frequency after installation; ongoing compliance is assessed through inspection rather than routine retesting. The annual main inspection should include surfacing assessment — depth measurements for loose-fill, visual inspection of unitary surfaces for cracking and separation, and evidence of contamination or drainage issues. In situ HIC testing can be commissioned where there is a specific concern, typically when surfacing has reached the end of its expected service life or after a significant incident.",
  },
  {
    q: "Is grass an acceptable playground surface?",
    a: "At low fall heights, yes. Well-maintained grass on suitable substrate can serve as an acceptable play surface for equipment with a critical fall height of 600 mm or below. Above that, grass does not provide adequate impact attenuation — the underlying soil is typically too hard, particularly in dry summers, and compaction under repeated use further reduces performance. For equipment above 600 mm CFH, impact-attenuating surfacing tested to BS EN 1177 is required.",
  },
  {
    q: "What is the HIC value and why does it matter?",
    a: "HIC stands for Head Injury Criterion. It is the measurement used in BS EN 1177 testing to characterise the severity of a head impact on a surface. Lower HIC values mean lower injury risk. BS EN 1177 testing drops a weighted headform onto the surface from the rated fall height and measures the resulting HIC value; the surface passes if the HIC stays below the threshold the standard specifies. For practical inspection purposes, the HIC test result is already baked into the manufacturer&rsquo;s rated fall height — inspectors check that the installed surfacing matches the measured CFH of the equipment above it, not that the HIC is recomputed on-site.",
  },
  {
    q: "What counts as the impact area around equipment?",
    a: "The impact area extends beyond the footprint of the equipment itself to cover where a child could foreseeably land after a fall. For most static equipment it extends at least 1.5 m beyond the equipment in all directions. For swings and similar moving equipment the impact area extends further in the direction of travel, and is shaped by the equipment&rsquo;s movement envelope. Surfacing must meet the CFH rating across the whole impact area — not just directly beneath the equipment. Inspectors frequently find that surfacing meets spec at the centre but thins, migrates or becomes bare at the edges of the impact zone.",
  },
];

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  mainEntity: faqs.map((item) => ({
    "@type": "Question",
    name: item.q,
    acceptedAnswer: {
